caption.text:
Baked cheesecakeğŸ‘ŒğŸ’ğŸ“ğŸ° Ingredients 
150g digestive biscuits 
75g butter, plus extra for greasing 500g cream cheese 
200g caster sugar 
250ml fresh cream 
2 tbsp plain flour 
2 eggs 
2 tsp custard powder
1 tbsp lemon juice Â Method 
Preheat the oven to 180C
Grease and line the base of a 23cm spring form cake tin. 
Place the biscuits in a plastic bag and crush with a rolling pin to fine crumbs. Melt the butter and add the biscuit crumbs, stir to combine. Place in the base of the cake tin and spread in an even layer, then flatten.
In a large bowl, beat together the cream cheese and sugar until smooth then add the fresh cream and flour and beat again. Gradually add the eggs, then add custard powder and lemon juice. Beat well between each addition. Pour the cream cheese mix on to the biscuit base then bake in the oven for 30 minutes. Reduce the heat to 150C then bake for another 30 minutes.
Turn off the oven and leave the cheesecake to cool inside.
Once the oven is cool you can remove the cheesecake to cool completely before removing from the tin. Decorate with fruits and drizzle with white chocolate.

Created by and Reposted from @functional.foods 
To make the VEGAN SPAGHETTI SQUASH LASAGNA, you will need:
â€¢ 1 spaghetti squash
â€¢ @miyokos_kitchen vegan mozzarella
â€¢ 1 jar @raoshomemade marinara sauce
â€¢ 3-4 cups chopped Swiss chard
â€¢ Fresh chopped basil (top)
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Pre-heat oven to 400Â°F. Cut the spaghetti squash lengthwise from stem to tail and scrape out the seeds and stringy bits of flesh.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Place the squash halves face down in a roasting pan and add enough water to lightly coat the bottom of the pan. Cook 30-40 minutes or until squash is tender.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
When the squash is done, remove from oven and let cool for 30 minutes before handling.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Next, lightly grease a 9x13 casserole dish with a bit of coconut oil. Start by creating the base layer with one half of the spaghetti squash (use a fork to scrape out strands). Spread squash evenly (semi-compact) followed by a layer of @miyokos_kitchen mozz. I used half the cheeze for the first layer and the other half for the second layer. I layered the cheeze chunks out about 1 1/2-2 inches apart.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Next, chop up ~1 1/2 cup of Swiss chard and lay evenly over the spaghetti squash and cheeze. Pour 1/2 a can of @raoshomemade marinara sauce over the Swiss chard. This is all the â€œfirst layer.â€
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Repeat the above steps to create the â€œsecond layerâ€ starting with the other half of spaghetti squash. Make sure the top layer is sauce.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Cover the dish with a small baking sheet (could cover the dish with foil but I donâ€™t use aluminum in cooking) and bake for 20 minutes at 400Â°F. Next, remove the sheet/foil and bake for an additional 10 minutes uncovered.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Once done, turn the oven setting to HIGH broil and cook for ~2 minutes (this gets the mozz browned and bubbly).
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Remove from heat, let cool. Top with fresh basil. Enjoy!

My favourite way to dress a salad:
Lemon juice from a large lemon, 1 tsp of hot red chilli powder, a pinch of turmeric and black pepper, extra virgin olive oil roughly equal to the volume of lemon juice, crushed sea salt to taste, chopped green chilli and lots of coriander for a fresh flavour! Let the salad soak in the dressing before eating.

1. Mix egg whites from carton with spices of choice, chopped spinach.

2. Glaze a pan with olive oil. Let pan heat up.

4. Peel off pan with plastic or rubber spatula and plate with guacamole or sauce of choice. 
5. Bon appetit!

caption.text:
Baked cheesecakeğŸ‘ŒğŸ’ğŸ“ğŸ° Ingredients 
150g digestive biscuits 
75g butter, plus extra for greasing 500g cream cheese 
200g caster sugar 
250ml fresh cream 
2 tbsp plain flour 
2 eggs 
2 tsp custard powder
1 tbsp lemon juice Â Method 
Preheat the oven to 180C
Grease and line the base of a 23cm spring form cake tin. 
Place the biscuits in a plastic bag and crush with a rolling pin to fine crumbs. Melt the butter and add the biscuit crumbs, stir to combine. Place in the base of the cake tin and spread in an even layer, then flatten.
In a large bowl, beat together the cream cheese and sugar until smooth then add the fresh cream and flour and beat again. Gradually add the eggs, then add custard powder and lemon juice. Beat well between each addition. Pour the cream cheese mix on to the biscuit base then bake in the oven for 30 minutes. Reduce the heat to 150C then bake for another 30 minutes.
Turn off the oven and leave the cheesecake to cool inside.
Once the oven is cool you can remove the cheesecake to cool completely before removing from the tin. Decorate with fruits and drizzle with white chocolate.

I have tested out many ways to seperate egg yolks from the whites, and there are some amazing gadgets out there but I always revert back to the same technique. I crack all the eggs into a bowl and then simply use my hands to take out the yolks. The whites slide through your finger tips and the yolk reminds in your palm. .
A few pointers though: * be careful not to crack the yolk when cracking the egg as it will then mess up all the whites. * if you arenâ€™t confident cracking all the eggs into one bowl then crack one egg at a time and then add the whites to a big bowl. * make sure your eggs are fresh before cracking them all into one bowl - all you need is one bad egg to spoil an entire bowl of eggs. * for a clean finish, pinch your fingers together to â€˜cutâ€™ off the white from the yolk when separating.

I have tested out many ways to seperate egg yolks from the whites, and there are some amazing gadgets out there but I always revert back to the same technique. I crack all the eggs into a bowl and then simply use my hands to take out the yolks. The whites slide through your finger tips and the yolk reminds in your palm. .
A few pointers though: * be careful not to crack the yolk when cracking the egg as it will then mess up all the whites. * if you arenâ€™t confident cracking all the eggs into one bowl then crack one egg at a time and then add the whites to a big bowl. * make sure your eggs are fresh before cracking them all into one bowl - all you need is one bad egg to spoil an entire bowl of eggs. * for a clean finish, pinch your fingers together to â€˜cutâ€™ off the white from the yolk when separating.

.
I have tested out many ways to seperate egg yolks from the whites, and there are some amazing gadgets out there but I always revert back to the same technique. I crack all the eggs into a bowl and then simply use my hands to take out the yolks. The whites slide through your finger tips and the yolk reminds in your palm. .
A few pointers though: * be careful not to crack the yolk when cracking the egg as it will then mess up all the whites. * if you arenâ€™t confident cracking all the eggs into one bowl then crack one egg at a time and then add the whites to a big bowl. * make sure your eggs are fresh before cracking them all into one bowl - all you need is one bad egg to spoil an entire bowl of eggs. * for a clean finish, pinch your fingers together to â€˜cutâ€™ off the white from the yolk when separating.
